{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522962"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13861"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13861"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.03,0.09,0.69,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6478"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13861"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32820"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"846"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12844"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 90-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with her daughter, who has concerns about a skin lesion on her mother\u0027s left breast. The patient is a nursing home resident and is pleasantly confused. Her daughter reports noticing the lesion recently while showering her mother, but is unsure how long it has been present. The patient has no other symptoms. She has a medical history of hypertension, osteoarthritis, and mild dementia. She takes amlodipine, paracetamol, and donepezil regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 1.5 cm brown, well-demarcated lesion with a waxy, slightly raised surface located on the left breast, just below the nipple (Image). The lesion does not blanch with pressure. There is no surrounding erythema or tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malignant melanoma","Paget\u0027s disease of the breast","Dermatofibroma","Seborrheic keratosis","Actinic keratosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this patient is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eseborrheic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E. These are benign epidermal tumours that commonly occur in older adults. They typically appear as well-demarcated, brown or black lesions with a waxy appearance, which matches the description in this case. While the duration of the lesion is uncertain due to the patient\u0027s cognitive status, the characteristic appearance strongly suggests a seborrheic keratosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as an irregularly shaped, asymmetrical lesion with variable coloration and often shows rapid growth or changes. These features are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of the breast\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare form of breast cancer that affects the nipple and areola. It typically presents as a red, scaly, itchy rash on the nipple that can extend to the areola. The well-demarcated, brown, waxy lesion described in this scenario is not consistent with Paget\u0027s disease and neither the nipple or the areola are involved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is typically a firm, round, brownish to reddish-purple growth. While it can be confused with seborrheic keratosis, it usually feels firm when pinched and does not have the waxy appearance described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActinic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a rough, scaly patch on sun-exposed areas and is a precursor to squamous cell carcinoma. It does not match the description of a well-demarcated, waxy lesion in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Seborrheic keratoses are benign epidermal tumors that commonly occur in older adults and have a characteristic waxy, raised appearance.","Seborrheic keratoses can be differentiated from malignant lesions by their well-defined borders, waxy or scaly surface, and lack of rapid growth or changes."],"references":["Aspres N. Sebborrhoeic keratoses. The Australian College of Dermatologists. 2019. Available online: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/seborrhoeic-keratoses/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32820"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13861"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20807"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20807"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/IsHxloM8zPUzLw4PqjqIxra5HFLdGF.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/IsHxloM8zPUzLw4PqjqIxra5HFLdGF.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32820"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-04T08:20:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-04T08:20:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6478"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48079"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"